The problem and a discussion¶

An accident could be happened to everyone at everytime in everywhere. But if we could collect the vast amount of accident data, we might be able to gain some insights that can be useful to reduce the number of accident or the fatality of the accident. There are many factors that are responsible for the existence of an accident, those are weather, road condition, light condition, etc. These factor can be strongly related to the severity of an accident, but some might be not. So, we need to find out what factor that directly related to the severity of an accident before predicting it.

In this project, we will try to predict the severity of an accident from the given dataset. This project will be a classification task where we will predict a categorical target.

The description of the data¶

The dataset that we have to use in this project should contain factors that we have been explained above, so we use opensource data that can be found here [url]. These data consist of almost 200.000 observations and almost 40 columns. Lets begin by importing libraries and load our data.

There you go. We get 'unknown' value from several attributes that we have to take care of. How to fix that? Well, first of all we can change it into NaN value since we have no clue of that value and we have two option from that, which is remove it or fill it.

Another problem occurs in JUNCTIONTYPE where we have 4 unique values rather than 2. So, we adjust the value.

If you notice, in 'INATTENTIONID' and 'SPEEDING' columns, there is only 1 unique value, which is Y for yes and the rest of it is just Nan value. We pretty sure that this nan value should be N for no, so we simply change it from nan to no.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

In this section we will perform data analysis using univariate and bivariate technique. We are going to dive deep into this dataset and gain some insight before build our machine learning model.

Univariate Analysis¶

From visualizations above, we can see that low severity (code: 1) is dominating the data. This means the dataset have unbalance class/category in target variable. So we might want to balance that before put it into our model. Another insight from above figures is that the most accidents regardless its level of severity occured when the condition (weather, light, road, etc) seems normal. This is not we initially tought and we will see deeper analysis in the next part.

Discussion Section¶

The output of our model was not really satisfying. Low model's accuracy can be caused by many factors, one of them would be unfit dataset like we have above. Therefore, it is tremendously important to select attributes or feautres in the proccess of getting or collecting the dataset. What happened to our dataset was that it has no any strong relationship. Lets take severity and weather as an example. We naturally think that weather and severity of an accident should have linear relationship, which means if we have a bad weather, the accident will tend to be more severe. That should also happen to other variables, such as road condition, light condition, etc. But, as we analyze our data, we found that our natural imagination turn to be false. Our data indicate that there is no relationship between weather and the level of severity of an accident. The severity level (code 1 & 2) are distributed equally in every weather condition, especially after we over-sampled our data. We also found that the highest number of an accident was happen when the condition seems normal.
